04510nam a22007575i 9780824863456DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20022002hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248634567 a10.1515/97808248634562doi  a(DE-B1597)484618  a(OCoLC)1024029917  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aND2731.L66bC38 2003eb 7aART0190002bisacsh04a755/.943/09421932211 aCate, Sandra, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMaking Merit, Making Art :bA Thai Temple in Wimbledon /cSandra Cate. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2002] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (232 p.) :b54 illus., 50 in color  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tNotes on Transliteration -- tPreface -- t1. Finding a Place -- t2. Long-Distance Merit-Making -- t3. Thai Art and the Authority of the Past -- t4. From Buddhist Stories to Modern Art -- t5. “Going Outside” and the Experience of Modernity -- t6. Art, Identity, and Performance -- t7. Tourists and Templegoers, Religion and Art -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSandra Cate's pioneering ethnography of art-making at Wat Buddhapadipa, a Thai Buddhist temple in Wimbledon, England, explores contemporary art at the crossroads of identity, authority, and value. Between 1984 and 1992, twenty-six young Thai artists painted a series of temple murals that continue to attract worshippers and tourists from around the world. Their work, both celebrated and controversial, depicts stories from the Buddha's lives in otherworldly landscapes punctuated with sly references to this-worldly politics and popular culture. Schooled in international art trends, the artists reverse an Orientalist narrative of the Asian Other, telling their own stories to diverse audiences and subsuming Western spaces into a Buddhist worldview.In her investigation of temple murals as social portraiture, Cate looks at the ongoing dialectic between the "real" and the "imaginary" as mural painters depict visual and moral hierarchies of sentient beings. As they manipulate indigenous notions of sacred space and the creative process, the Wat Buddhapadipa muralists generate complex, expansive visions of social place and identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBuddhist mural painting and decorationzEnglandzLondon. 0aMural painting and decoration, ThaizEnglandzLondony20th century. 7aART / Asian / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082486345640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824863456423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824863456.jpg  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-066325-9  University of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_AD  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_AD  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK